<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/rhythm/why-you-need-to-use-repeated-rhythms-within-your-grooves-bass-lines.html">Why You Need to Use Repeated Rhythms Within Your Grooves &#038; Bass Lines</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com">Online Bass Lessons</a>.</p>
]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/Rt8rCWNcwoM" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></p>
</p>
<h2 style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.scottsbasslessons.com/sbl-academy-checkout">&gt;&gt;&gt;Click Here and Get Access to the Full Course and Much More with your Free 14 Day Trial to the Academy&lt;&lt;&lt;</a></h2>
<p>
<p>===</p>
<h1>Lesson Overview</h1>
<p>You may think that using rhythmical repetition within your lines sounds simple at first, but trust me - I see countless bass players meandering around the fretboard with no real certainty, or solid groove and time feel within their playing. It makes their lines sound weak and ungrounded but I find that much of the time this is simply due to a lack of repeated rhythms being used.</p>
<p>Even the most <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/riff-of-the-week/twister-bass-riff-week-8.html" target="_blank">complex of bass lines</a> will keep returning to some sort of ‘centre’, some sort of rhythmical foundation. This is what creates the groove that as listeners put’s a smile on our face, get’s our feet tapping and our heads bobbing. Much of the time the ‘centre’ I'm talking about will be created by using repeated rhythmical figures within a groove or bass line.</p>
<p>In this lesson I explain the rhythmical grid that “Good Times” by Chic is based upon, and we look into using repetition within your lines to give you a more compositional approach when creating grooves, riffs and <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/bass-lines-grooves/danny-mo-morris-r-b-bass-lesson.html" target="_blank">bass lines</a>.</p>
<p>If you’re interested in taking the rhythmical side of your playing to a completely new level you should also check out my “Groove Formula” course within <a href="http://scottsbasslessons.com/bass-academy" target="_blank">the Academy</a> here as Scott’s Bass Lessons. In fact the lesson you’re watching right now is taken directly from that course. In a nutshell, it’s the most in-depth course focused around groove and bass line creation ever created.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h1>Your Homework</h1>
<p>What are your all time favourite bass lines or riffs?</p>
<p>Is it, or are they, built using some sort of repeated rhythmical pattern?</p>
<p>Let me know in the comments below!</p>
<p>As always, see you in the shed…</p>
<p>Scott</p>
