		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://scottsbasslessons.com/?p=1156</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>When playing walking bass lines, your feel is absolutely key to make everything 'sit' as it should within the context of whichever ensemble you're playing. The exercises presented within this lesson should help you on your way to strengthening your...</p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/rhythm/walking-bass-swing-feel.html">Walking Bass &#8211; Improve Your Swing Feel! (L#20)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com">Online Bass Lessons</a>.</p>
]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>When playing <a href="https://www.scottsbasslessons.com/walking-bass-lines/walking-bass-beginner-2.html">walking bass lines</a>, your feel is absolutely key to make everything 'sit' as it should within the context of whichever ensemble you're playing. The exercises presented within this lesson should help you on your way to strengthening your internal clock and improving your walking bass swing feel.</p>
<p>Whether you've already watched my other <a title="Walking Bass Series" href="https://www.scottsbasslessons.com/walking-bass-lines/walking-bass-beginner-1.html">lessons on walking bass</a> or not, this one is very important: you can play all the 'right' notes, simple or more sophisticated walking bass lines, if your swing feel isn't good enough, it's gonna sound like... well, it won't sound as good as it should. ;)</p>
<p><div><a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/bass-academy" class="post_cta">Full tab/notation & workbook available to Academy members &raquo;</a></div><div class="video_wrap "><iframe src="//www.youtube.com/embed/QEthHtlNDDs" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></div><br />
</p>
